│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                                                                                                                 │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                                                                                                     │
│ The crash occurs during verification after SLP vectorization, with the message 'Instruction does not dominate all uses!'. The problematic IR shows a newly      │
│ created shufflevector (%3) used by an add instruction (%2) in a context where the definition does not dominate its use. This indicates that the SLP vectorizer  │
│ introduced an instruction at an insertion point that is too late relative to some of its consumers in the same basic block or in predecessor blocks.            │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                                                                                                         │
│ The verifier rejects the module post-transformation. The first failing construct is a shuffle inserted by the vectorizer. The pass pipeline only runs SLP; thus │
│ the first IR mutation belongs to SLP. The relevant code region handling shuffle emission for buildvector (insertelement) reconstruction is around lines         │
│ 16609–16642 in SLPVectorizer.cpp. There, the code sets the IRBuilder insertion point to 'LastInsert' (the last insertelement instruction in a sorted chain)     │
│ before creating the replacement shuffle sequence. Later, it rebuilds or replaces the buildvector chain and rewires uses. If any existing user of the vectorized │
│ value (or scalar slated for replacement) appears earlier in the same block (or in a dominating block expecting the original chain root), inserting at the last  │
│ insertelement may result in the new instruction appearing after some of its uses. This is consistent with the dominance failure.                                │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                                                                                                         │
│ The algorithm chooses the insertion point using:                                                                                                                │
│   InsertElementInst *FirstInsert = ...;                                                                                                                         │
│   InsertElementInst *LastInsert = ...;                                                                                                                          │
│   Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert);                                                                                                                           │
│ However, 'LastInsert' is the terminal insertelement of the original chain, not necessarily dominating all uses that are being rewired to the new shuffle        │
│ result. Users (including earlier instructions in the same block or PHI nodes expecting values from predecessor blocks) may appear before 'LastInsert'. When     │
│ 'User->replaceUsesOfWith' rewires operands to the newly created shuffle, those users may now refer to a value defined later in the block, violating dominance.  │
│ The safe insertion point must dominate all users. For a buildvector chain, every insertelement dominates later ones, but not vice versa. Thus picking the       │
│ earliest (first) insertelement—or computing a common dominator of all involved insert elements and their uses—is required. The current implementation always    │
│ picks the last, which can be too late.                                                                                                                          │
│ The minimal reproducer likely forms a trivial chain where a user appears before the last insertelement. The resulting shuffle is inserted after the user,       │
│ triggering the verifier error.                                                                                                                                  │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                                                                                                      │
│ Edit lines 16612–16616 in SLPVectorizer.cpp to change the insertion point from 'LastInsert' to a dominating position. A minimal corrective change is to use     │
│ 'FirstInsert' as the insertion point:                                                                                                                           │
│ Replace:                                                                                                                                                        │
│   Builder.SetInsertPoint(LastInsert);                                                                                                                           │
│ With:                                                                                                                                                           │
│   // Use the first insertelement as insertion point to guarantee dominance over                                                                                 │
│   // all subsequent buildvector components and existing users that may precede                                                                                  │
│   // the last insertelement. Using LastInsert may place the new shuffle after                                                                                   │
│   // some rewired users, violating dominance.                                                                                                                   │
│   Builder.SetInsertPoint(FirstInsert);                                                                                                                          │
│ If desired for future robustness, a more elaborate solution could compute the nearest common dominator of all InsertElements and their users, but for the       │
│ current failure switching to FirstInsert suffices and maintains ordering semantics of the original chain.                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                 │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                                                                                                  │
│ The dominance violation stems from choosing an insertion point (LastInsert) that does not necessarily dominate all rewired uses after replacing a buildvector   │
│ chain with a shuffle. Changing the insertion point to FirstInsert (which by construction dominates the rest of the chain and any earlier users) resolves the    │
│ verifier failure. This fix preserves correctness for buildvector reconstruction and prevents out-of-order definition/use relationships introduced by SLP in     │
│ this scenario.                                                                                                                                                  │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                                                                                                                 │
